{
  "text": "MicroRNAs (miRNAs or miRs) are a class of small noncoding RNAs that regulate gene expression by facilitating mRNA degradation or translational inhibition. They play important roles in development, cellular differentiation, proliferation, cell cycle control, and cell death [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and have been implicated in a variety of human diseases, including cancer [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Recent evidence suggests that the FOXO family of transcription factors are targets for regulation by miRs. For example, aberrant miR-182 expression has been implicated in melanoma metastasis through downregulation of FOXO3a [CITATION_5] . In addition, a number of studies reported altered patterns of miR expression in EEC and identified a subset of miRs that correlated with disease stage and recurrence [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Using an in silico approach, we identified several cross-species conserved miRs predicted to target the 3\u2032-untranslated region (UTR) of FOXO1. In both clinical samples and endometrial cancer cell lines, we investigated the role of miRs in the deregulation of FOXO1 expression and activity in endometrial cancer.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "18375348",
    "[CITATION_2]": "19525479",
    "[CITATION_3]": "19525479",
